1. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper deals with the problem of identifying active subcarriers in an OFDM signal from compressive measurements, which is a problem related to information theory. 
2. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The problem of identifying active subcarriers in an OFDM signal is relevant to networking and communication systems, which fall under the domain of networking and internet architecture. 
3. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) - The paper deals with the problem of identifying active subcarriers in an OFDM signal, which is a problem related to signal processing and can be applied to social and information networks. 
4. cs.LG (Machine Learning) - The paper proposes an Orthogonal Matching Pursuit (OMP)-based joint sparse recovery method for identifying active subcarriers, which is a machine learning technique. 
5. cs.MM (Multimedia) - The problem of identifying active subcarriers in an OFDM signal is relevant to multimedia applications, which require efficient use of available spectrum.
